{
  "title": "Problems of Form",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f9be09df903579f9",
      "text": "This is a book of essays by primarily German scholars working in the tradition of the late [[Niklas Luhmann]]. Indeed, he is the author of two of the contributions. The volume has a very specific focus. All the contributions, including those by Luhmann, discuss conceptual and empirical problems dealing with the attempt to relate Luhmann's \"system theory\" to \"the calculus of indications\" set out by [[George Spencer-Brown]] in The [[Laws of Form]] (1969)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5a0e5f295ab36aa2",
      "text": "Luhmann's interest in this calculus can be understood in terms of his interest in general systems thinking. In the 1950s and 1960s, much of general systems thinking focused on [[Cybernetics]]. This development had an impact on sociological theory in numerous ways, including some research programs that are thriving at this time. For instance, David Heise's affect control theory and Peter Burke's social identity theory each employ a negative feedback model informed by the brilliant 1973 cybernetic treatise Behavior: The Control of Perception, by William T. Powers. Perhaps later developments in general systems thinking will have a similar impact in the coming decades."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "61a56f72bc4b39c9",
      "text": "In the 1970s and 1980s, one development in general systems thinking involved attempts to move beyond homeostasis to undertake the generalized study of biological dynamic systems under the category \"[[Autopoiesis]].\" A prominent figure in this later development is [[Francesco Varela]] who, in his Principles of Biological Autonomy, characterizes an autopoetic system as one that distinguishes itself from its environment and in doing so \"continuously generates and specifies its own organization through its operation as a system of production of its own components, and does this in an endless turnover of components under conditions of continuous perturbations and compensation of perturbations\" (1979:13)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "16452e02f1e8ac42",
      "text": "This sounds very much like what happens in the type of system we call a society, and that is exactly the point of Luhmann's attempt to reformulate the theory of social systems in terms of autopoiesis. Both Varela, using formal methods, and Luhmann, informally, have referred to Spencer-Brown's calculus in pursuit of their common conceptual enterprise, the former in biology and the latter in sociology. This takes us back to the book under review."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a2142a7fd40a069f",
      "text": "The contributors to Problems of Form seem to regard Spencer-Brown's calculus of indications as the mathematical foundation of Luhmann's system theory. For instance, the editor's opening statement, \"Mathematics has often attracted sociologists,\" leads one to anticipate a development in the formalization of Luhmann's complex theory in terms of Spencer-Brown's calculus. But from that point of view, the volume is a disappointment. Despite much discussion, there is no real use of the formal apparatus with its promise of treating complex systems of recursively generated forms relating to acts that create distinctions. The editor provides a nonformal brief introduction to certain key ideas of the calculus of indications, but this is not enough to generate an intuitive grasp of unfamiliar notions drawn from the book by Spencer-Brown."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6709d28e328fe470",
      "text": "But any attempt to engage that book must be ready to confront a somewhat enigmatic entity. What Spencer-Brown is doing, at a purely formal level, is proposing a new axiomatization of Boolean algebra, based upon a very limited number of axioms. Extensions of the algebra lead into such intriguing notions as a Boolean counterpart to imaginary numbers. Spencer-Brown also thinks he is solving the problems of the foundations of mathematics, a topic that concerned one of his teachers, Bertrand Russell. Perhaps Russell saw in him a second Wittgenstein and looked forward to the birth of a new Tractatus. Indeed, with an air of mystery that is never quite resolved, Chapter 1 of The Laws of Form opens with the proclamation, \"Distinction is perfect continence,\" a statement explicitly labeled in boldface as a \"definition.\""
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8a373f54bbdb79ec",
      "text": "Checking to see if Spencer-Brown's book might still be in print, I found that at Amazon.com, one enthusiastic volunteer reviewer calls the book one of the three greatest of the century. The World Wide Web rewards the searcher with a web page devoted to a kind of Spencer-Brown cult. Intrigued, I consulted the original reviews in academic journals. The philosopher L. L. Whyte, writing in The British Journal for the Philosophy of Science proclaimed the book \"a work of genius\" while also admitting that he was not capable of passing judgment on its formal algebraic contents. In The Journal of Symbolic Logic, the reviewer did manage to penetrate the formalism, noting a variety of invalid inferences in it as well as missing axioms required to carry through the valid deductions. It came as no surprise, then, to learn that Spencer-Brown's calculus has played no role in later treatments of the foundations of mathematics and logic, whatever significance it may yet have for the formalization of Luhmann's theory."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d9460b99c0aed6b7",
      "text": "What is the upshot of all this? Marginal figures producing works of genius are not unknown. Experts can be too conservative in their judgments. A cult can have good reason to admire a neglected figure. Serious scholars, such as those contributing to Problems of Form, can ignore obscure elements and concentrate on conceptual insights. And yet, the combination of dense prose that conveys Luhmann's complex theory and a formal calculus with dubious internal validity do not sound like a good bet for a future breakthrough in mathematical social theory."
    },
