      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "5a0e5f295ab36aa2",
        "text": "Luhmann's interest in this calculus can be understood in terms of his interest in general systems thinking. In the 1950s and 1960s, much of general systems thinking focused on cyberetics. This development had an impact on sociological theory in numerous ways, including some research programs that are thriving at this time. For instance, David Heise's affect control theory and Peter Burke's social identity theory each employ a negative feedback model informed by the brilliant 1973 cybernetic treatise Behavior: The Control of Perception, by William T. Powers. Perhaps later developments in general systems thinking will have a similar impact in the coming decades. In the 1970s and 1980s, one development in general systems thinking involved attempts to move beyond homeostasis to undertake the generalized study of biological dynamic systems under the category \"autopoiesis.\" A prominent figure in this later development is Francesco Varela who, in his Principles of Biological Autonomy, characterizes an autopoetic system as one that distinguishes itself from its environment and in doing so \"continuously generates and specifies its own organization through its operation as a system of production of its own components, and does this in an endless turnover of components under conditions of continuous perturbations and compensation of perturbations\" (1979:13)."
