      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "8a373f54bbdb79ec",
        "text": "Checking to see if Spencer-Brown's book might still be in print, I found that at Amazon.com, one enthusiastic volunteer reviewer calls the book one of the three greatest of the century. The World Wide Web rewards the searcher with a web page devoted to a kind of Spencer-Brown cult. Intrigued, I consulted the original reviews in academic journals. The philosopher L. L. Whyte, writing in The British Journal for the Philosophy of Science proclaimed the book \"a work of genius\" while also admitting that he was not capable of passing judgment on its formal algebraic contents. In The Journal of Symbolic Logic, the reviewer did manage to penetrate the formalism, noting a variety of invalid inferences in it as well as missing axioms required to carry through the valid deductions. It came as no surprise, then, to learn that Spencer-Brown's calculus has played no role in later treatments of the foundations of mathematics and logic, whatever significance it may yet have for the formalization of Luhmann's theory."
